\par }\pard\plain \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sb100\sa100\sbauto1\saauto1\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1004843 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs20\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \fs24\lang1033\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp1033\langfenp2057 {
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Born 19}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  March 1932 in New End Hospital Hampstead}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\sa120\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1004843 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
Father a quite junior civil servant in the Ministry of Health, specifically doing pensions. Mother had been a secretary and founded a secretarial agency, which she gave up when she found out she was pregnant. 
\par History of Grandparents is particularly complicated. His father was illegitimate. His grandfather \endash  he has discovered \endash 
 was Georg Heinrich Peter Vollmer, a button merchant with a warehouse in Manchester, where his grandmother had been working. His father was then known as Arthur Vickers Hall and was a
dopted by a Baptist family in Disley and left school at 14 or 15. He seems to have had a theatrical period in his life, though little known about it. Was an \lquote Edwardian gent\rquote  \endash 
 always beautifully dressed with a very posh accent. Herr Volmer had continued to provide for him in some way, leaving money in his will for him on strict condition that he didn\rquote 
t make a career on the stage. Used to visit an aunt in Trafford in the 1940s who was, in fact, his grandmother. 
\par Mother was born into a very large family. Maternal grandfather was Thomas Keefe, a warehouse man who committed suicide. Mother therefore had to leave school at fifteen (even though her teachers had hoped she\rquote 
d go on to university). Great grandfather, according to family legend, was the illegitimate son of the Earl of Lonsdale. Maternal grandmother had no birth certificate and was adopted. The family story is that she was the daughte}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1004843 r of an Anglesey horse dealer (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 thief}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid1004843 ?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 ).
\par As far as influence on him was concerned \endash  he didn\rquote t know who his paternal grandfather was, his paternal grandmother was his \lquote aunt\rquote 
 whom he only saw once a year (in a creepy Victorian house), his maternal grandfather died before he was born and his maternal grandmother lived with his aunt and uncle in a slum house in Eccles and didn\rquote t have any influence on him. 
\par Parents moved from Hampstead to West Hampstead and then West Kensington. His first memory is his father lifting him up to see the Piccadilly line trains coming out of the tunnel between the District Line trains between West Kensi
ngton and Barons Court station and then playing on the floor at home with two hairbrushes, one representing a Piccadilly Line train, the other a District Line train. Became obsessed by the underground. Then moved to Wimbledon.
\par Went to a small private schoo
l in Wimbledon. In 1940 his father was required to report at Euston Station to leave for a secret destination (the whole Civil Service being moved outside the range of possible Luftwaffe attacks). After three months they discovered he was in Blackpool and
 went to join him there. Went to primary school in Blackpool and the Grammar school from 1943-1950.
\par A very traditional grammar school and a very good one. The standard of education was unbelievable by modern standards because most of the teachers were recru
ited during the 1920s and 1930s when teaching was one of the best jobs around. Taught by men who would have been university teachers fifty years on. 
\par Age 13, the school divided into an arts side and science side. Entered arts side. At sixth form went into \lquote The Sixth Modern\rquote  which was history, geography and economics. Taught economics in a class of six \endash 
 like a constant tutorial. Donald Murdoch, History Master, was a huge influence. Absolutely inspiring. An Oxford graduate of 1920s, hysterical character who 
was a Communist turned Trotskyist after the Stalinist show trials. History lessons interspersed with bizarre pieces of advice about what to do when the revolution came. Taught history from an extremely Marxist perspective \endash 
 all about class warfare. Really wanted to do history at University but teacher didn\rquote t have much influence at his Oxford college whereas the Geography Master (farmer manqu\'e9, uninspiring teacher) had connections with St. Catharine\rquote 
s Cambridge. As a result he went in for St. Catharine\rquote s exhibition and got it. 
\par Found himself arriving at St. Catherine\rquote s to read Geography. Considers himself a historian manqu\'e9 and a bit of an economist manqu\'e9. Went back to history more and more \endash  managing to weave history and geography into a narrative. Everythi
ng he did subsequently had history woven into it. Believes that you can\rquote t plan without understanding the deep structures that control what you\rquote re able to do in planning. 
\par Hated the first year \endash  physical geography. Were used as unpaid research assistants going out on disagreeable trips. After the first year specialised in economic and historical geography. Taught by outstanding teacher \endash 
 Gus Caesar. Many of his pupils went on into academia. In his third year \endash  and for his PhD \endash  was taught by Clifford Smith who became a good friend. 
\par Got a double first in Part One and Part Two of the Tripos and got a state scholarship (to supplement the exhibition) for his PhD. Seemed obvious to go on \endash  liked research and was interested in historical geography. Went on to rese
arch the location of industries in London (which turned into his first book, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Industries of London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 ). Worked slavishly on historical records. The 1951 census came out after he\rquote 
d finished PhD so he had to update it afterwards for the sake of the book. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Industries of London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 was an impossible topic. Had been told it was impossible but stubbornly determined to do it. Used the Post Office London Directories, which showed the location of every individual company (and so could map the distribution of worksho
p industries). Also used a lot of historical evidence from the Victorian Royal Commissions and Charles Booth\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
Life and Labour of the People of London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . (Interestingly, Victorian Commissions were a result of concern about immigration 
\endash  in this case Jewish immigration.)
\par The Victorian censuses stopped being useful after 1861 and, when he started, the 1951 census wasn\rquote t ready. The critical industry tables were only produced after he finished the PhD. As a result his PhD was full of \lquote junky data\rquote 
. Fortunately, he was able to correct all this for the book.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
One of the most important influences on him was John Vaizey. Odd introduction when Vaizey (a new fellow) invited a number of graduates for coffee. He told them that he found the college a \lquote dead-beat dump\rquote  and couldn\rquote 
t stand the other fellows. The fellows had a book in which they summed up the graduates\rquote  characteristics and he had invited the ones they found \lquote absolutely weird\rquote 
 to coffee. He formed a weekly discussion club in which someone presented a topic each week. 
\par Vaizey wanted to promote him as his successor as Kenwood research fellow. Needed to persuade Alfred Steers, Professor of Geography. Arranged a sherry party for him to meet Steers. Unfortunately, Vaizey and his economics students had been out on the raz
zle the night before, celebrating tripos results, and everyone but Steers and Peter Hall were very }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid13849126\charrsid1004843 hangover}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . Vaizey ended up covering Steers in soda water and that was the end of his prospects. 
\par Entered the Civil Service in the Board of Trade and couldn\rquote t stand it. Hadn\rquote t finished the PhD because he got diverted into an interest in films in his last year at Cambridge and became the film critic for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Varsity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 newspaper. The following academic year applied for an assistant junior lectureship at UCL and didn\rquote t ge
t it. Had an interview at Birkbeck (having dictated his own reference to John Vaizey for the job). At interview, said he was willing to learn German and learn about the geography of Germany. Got the job. 
\par Became assistant lecturer in Geography, special reference Germany, at Birkbeck College. Had to start work again on his PhD. Managed to submit it and got the PhD in 1959. 
\par Became interested, around 1960, in planning questions. This was partly the indirect influence of Gus Caesar who had been involved in reg
ional policy during the war. Started teaching a course at Birkbeck on applied geography (really planning), focusing on regional and industrial location. Started to trace the story of the attempt to shift industry out of London after WW2 (the consequence o
f the Barlow Commission of 1940). This provided the basis for the final chapter of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Industries of London}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . Then became very interested in more recent economic geography. 
\par By then had become involved in politics. On the board of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Socialist Commentary}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  magazine (a bit like today\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Prospect}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
). Met a lot of LSE and Oxford academics through it. Started writing articles on London planning issues in 1960. Always keen on journalism. John Vaizey suggested he write a book on planning London and got him a contract with 
Faber and Faber. This was the genesis of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London 2000}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . 
\par His interest in industrial location and the distribution of economic (he says \lquote academic\rquote  meaning \lquote economic\rquote ) activity drew him towards an interest in planning. When he wrote about the \lquote industries\rquote 
 of London he was referring to the manufacturing industries. He\rquote d already realised, however, that the economy of London was shifting to a service base. He discovered that the Barlow commission had mixed up the meaning of the word \lquote industry
\rquote . Economists also used \lquote industry\rquote  to include service industries, producing services not goods. That fundamental confusion runs through the Barlow commission: they didn\rquote 
t realise that the growth of London was due to service industry. He became more and more interested in this question of what you could ever do about the service industries (which had different \lquote factors of location\rquote 
 from manufacturing industries). George Morton, at the LSE, was involved with Pergamon (Maxwell\rquote s press) in doing some classic reprints of works in economics. Suggested that he got into }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Isolated State}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 written by Johann Heinrich von Thuenen in 1826. 
\par Had married Carla Wartenberg in 1962. Got divorced soon after. But worked together on the translation of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Isolated State}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . That book made him even more interested in questions of theoretical industrial location. Thus in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8324751\charrsid1004843 mid-60s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 he was concerned with principles of location of industries, including service industries. Stemming from this was the question of what public policy could do about this. 
\par Very tied up with Labour Party Politics at the time. Joined the Fabian Society through the agency of Shirley Williams (then secretary). Was on the Fabian Home Policy Committee and then the Fabian Executive. Started helping George Brown in his leadership b
i
d (which failed). A chief plank of Labour policy was a more prescriptive approach to planning. Wilson created a new department of economic affairs as a counterweight to the Treasury (which would do the necessary for planned economic growth). The idea was 
to have a national plan and regional plans. They set up regional economic planning councils. In late \rquote 
65 was asked to join the South East Planning Council. Was very involved in shaping government policy, in particular concerning the growth of London and the growth of service industries (i.e. offices). 
\par He was idealistic. But it was all associated with a spirit of the time, difficult to capture now. People quote Harold Wilson: \lquote the white heat of techonology\rquote . Labour then presented itself as the young party, t
he serious party of the new class of technocrats. The Prime Minister, Alec Douglas Home, was presented as part of the failing aristocratic order, due to be swept away. They were all very committed to the notion of modernisation, including physical moderni
s
ation. England was then very, very physically clapped out. London was filthy, shabby and basically Victorian. There was a feeling that all this had to be swept away and replaced by a new Britain. Cities had to be rebuilt totally. They also believed in bui
lding motorways. 
\par In 1955, while still a graduate in Cambridge, he had been on a rail tour of Scandinavia and became interested in Scandinavia as an example of planned cities. Loved Stockholm and felt very inspired by it. That visit was one of the most impo
rtant influences of his life, making him committed to the vision of planned development. Started him on the route of being a planner. He wasn\rquote t indifferent to really historic buildings (e.g. felt that St. Paul\rquote 
s Cathedral should be preserved) but wasn\rquote t that bothered about general preservation (e.g. suspects he wasn\rquote 
t bothered about Euston Station). The whole idea was to create the modernist city. He was also committed to the idea of building motorways. All of this came into }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London 2000.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The idea of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London 2000}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 was to write a book about London planning. The central thesis was that London was going to continue to grow and therefore its growth needed to be planned for. An unfashionable position. The Barlow Commission, and post-war government, had intended London
\rquote s growth to be limited, stopped by the green belt, with some new towns being built outside. By the late}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2037852  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid2037852\charrsid1004843 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 50s, already clear that this wasn
\rquote t working \endash  there was continued rapid growth in the London region. In 1960 A.G. Powell wrote a paper saying that g
overnment had to plan for this growth. The Conservative government then began trying to plan for the future of London, resisted by the Labour Party. He became a voice of the Labour party, saying that it couldn\rquote 
t be stopped. This made him very unpopular with the \lquote old Labour Barons from the North\rquote  who thought everything should be up in the North of England. 
\par The main thesis of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London 2000}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  was that London couldn\rquote t grow within London, so needed to extend into new towns. He argued for 28 new towns around London,
 extending much farther out. That never happened \endash  one or two did get build roughly where he suggested \endash  because policy shifted a lot. He shifted his own views in \rquote 66,\rquote 
67 about how it was to be done and did influence planning policy through the South East Planning Council 
\par The book was based on documentary research, not field work. He just looked at the numbers. Calls himself a \lquote number cruncher\rquote . He looks at the numbers and the trends. Passionately believes that you need to look at the deep trends and see w
hat you can do to move them. Can\rquote t stop them \endash  King Canute style \endash  but can influence them. 
\par Taught applied geography at Birkbeck until \rquote 65. Went to LSE in \rquote 66. LSE had decided that it should launch a new Masters course in Regional and Urban planning studie
s. Launched this with Alan Day, Professor of Economics, and Peter Self, Professor of Politics (and father of Will). The first of the new planning courses \endash  anti the Royal Town Planning Institute courses \endash 
 based on the notion that planning should be scientific and based on close economic and social analysis. 
\par At the same time, was very involved in setting up the Regional Studies Association in 1966. First editor of their periodical, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
Regional Studies}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . All part of the same spirit of a new approach to planning. 
\par The LSE had a cosy common room. Got on well with Alan Day, Emrys Jones, Bernard Donoghue, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid16350624 M}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 aurice Peston (father of Robert) and Michael }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid2037852\charrsid6447803 Beesley}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . Finished }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
World Cities}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  while at LSE, but had already spent a lot of time working on it at Birkbeck. The term \lquote world cities\rquote 
 had been invented by Patrick Geddes, crazy Scots visionary planner, in 1915, but had fallen into disuse. Wanted to establish that there were certain very important cities in a special category because they did different \lquote things\rquote 
 from other cities. It was an idea he exhumed which has been extensively used since (interchangeable with the term \lquote global cities\rquote 
). Thinks he can claim that it was original work. A study of how cities planned their own growth. One of his more \lquote journalistic\rquote  books and a
 favourite of his. Considers himself as much an academic journalist as a true academic. Has always written for an imaginary intelligent member of public. 
\par In 1963 met Tim Raison \endash  then editor of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 New Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  magazine (weekly magazine of the social sciences) \endash 
 who asked him to write an article about European growth. When Tim stood down, Paul Barker replaced him (becoming a good friend). It was a very important publication having a very big circulation and devoted to making the social sciences intelligible. Wr
ote a short column every week for the magazine, including many longer articles (some of which he sees as the most important things he\rquote s ever written). 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 [The most significant, or at any rate most widely-quoted, of these was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Nonplan: an Experiment in Freedom }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
(1969), written jointly with Paul Barker, Reyner Banham and Cedric Price, arguing that }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
much town and country planning was misguided and counter-productive and should be scrapped.  It has had major influence over the succeeding 40 years, not least in the current government\rquote 
s (2011) reform of the system.  It was followed by a lecture to the Royal Town Planning Institute at their 1977 annual conference, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\cf1\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
Green Fields and Grey Areas}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang9\langfe1033\langnp9\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
, which the subsequent Conservative Chancellor of the Exchequer, Sir Geoffrey Howe, argued was the origin of the Thatcher government\rquote s Enterprise Zone proposals.  I dem
urred at that, but there was a philosophical thread leading through these events].}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\cf1\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
Reading University was expanding rapidly. Being there was like being at a new university. Had just relocated to a new campus. Very exciting to run a department there \endash  felt 
you could do things. Reading had just taken over the College of Estate Management (teaching valuation). Established a new faculty \endash  the Faculty of Urban and Regional Studies \endash  with the Estate Managers. 
\par Became friendly with John Dunning (Professor of Economics) and Charles Miles (Professor of Valuations). Took his turn as Dean of the Faculty of Urban and Regional Studies. A lovely university \endash 
 very happy there. Peter Fellgett (Professor of Cybernetics) shared his interest in control systems. There was then a belief that planning was about controlling complex systems. Many departmental colleagues (e.g. David Starkie) were friends. 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Great Planning Disasters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  came out at the end of his time at Reading. In the late 1970s the whole intellectual underpinnings of pl
anning were turned upside down. Top down controlling attitude to planning was suddenly seen as wrong. The tide turned against the idea of motorways programme and a third airport for London. Had been very involved in the case for a third airport. In 1977 t
he Planning Council argued for three priorities \endash 
 building an airport at Stansted, the M25 and a development corporation for London Docklands. Made him very unpopular. Two years later Thatcher came to power and disbanded the Planning Councils (her advisor c
laiming, wrongly, that they were hotbeds of Marxist conspiracy). She then followed their proposals, including Stansted Airport. He ended up giving evidence at a public enquiry, being cross examined by friends from the Town and Country Planning Association
. All of this got him thinking about how planning decisions got taken and unpicked and then repacked and reinvented. And that was the basis of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Great Planning Disasters}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  book. 
\par The first half of the book was easy to write. The hard part was the second par
t where he entered totally new territory. Most interesting to him was Public Choice theory. Associated with a few academics, including Buchanan and Tulloch. They were interested in how individual values got aggregated to form political preferences. They d
eveloped a notion of intensity of preference \endash 
 arguing that a very few people would have extreme intensity of preference (generally for not doing something) whereas most people are not bothered. Intensity preference has no role in a democratic society but g
ives rise to lobbying. In this way economics and politics become melded. He found these ideas very difficult. How do you compare interpersonal utilities \endash  Bentham\rquote s pleasures and pains? If one person\rquote 
s displeasure is more intense than another\rquote s pleasure wh
at happens? He became both obsessed by it and beaten by it. Ended up dissatisfied with his final chapters. But the book was very influential, becoming part of the standard syllabus of planning schools. 
\par The story of Sydney Opera House \endash  an epic in cost escalation rising from 7 million Australian dollars to 102 million Australian dollars. They also didn\rquote 
t get the opera house they thought they were getting. However still a triumph in terms of symbolism. 
\par He first taught in Berkeley in 1974, invited by Mel Web
ber. Mel Webber was a major influence on his life. In 1963-64 Mel wrote two essays in which he argued that physical space meant less and less and there was already a class for which your associations were across the world and it didn\rquote 
t matter where. He reviewed his essays favourably and was invited to visit. 
\par In 1966 he was planning a major new enterprise at the think-tank PEP (Political and Economic Planning) which culminated in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
The Containment of Urban England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  in 1973. A huge research project resulting in
 a two volume book. Very difficult venture in practice. Plotting this out he went to talk to key people in the US regarding the new approaches in planning. Became great friends with Mel during this trip and as a result ended up teaching at Berkeley 
\endash  first for just a quarter and eventually full time (spurred to leave England by the Winter of Discontent). 
\par Berkeley was brilliant. It was the best university, best faculty and students in his experience. So questioning, so brilliant, so intelligent and able and energetic \endash 
 very energising. They were boom years in California. Being on the edge of Silicon Valley at that time was very invigorating. Everything felt possible. People were able to turn ideas into profit in an almost seamless operation. It was a place o
f risk taking and entrepreneurship. 
\par He was influenced in all kinds of ways by his time there. He switched towards high-tech research, starting with a collaboration with Ann Markusen. First worked together on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Silicon Landscapes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  (1985) and then }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 High Tech America}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  (1987), }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Western Sunrise}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  (1987) and finally }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
The Rise of the Gunbelt}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 (1991). The last was a bit of a flop; it was about the role of the Pentagon in fomenting high tech research and development, but was published at the end of the Cold War when that pha
se had ended and no one was interested. Now people are getting interested again. The Pentagon was enormously influential in the shift of production to the West Coast. For that book, went to Washington DC and saw growth of the Dulles corridor and Tysons Co
rner. Tysons Corner \lquote the most amazing place I have ever seen\rquote . Originally a gas station, by the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid16212032\charrsid1004843 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 80s it was the biggest downtown in the state of Virginia \endash  all created by Reagan\rquote 
s Star Wars. Star Wars involved intercepting an imagined Soviet threat from mis
siles using software. Vast numbers of software writers were needed who had to be within 10 minutes of the Pentagon. Tysons ended up high rise offices full of software writers. Fascinating stuff. The origin of sat nav!
\par Found I.T. fascinating and all-absorbing. Became obsessed around \rquote 83 with Kondratieff waves (main theme of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Carrier Wave}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 ) and was convinced that the next one was due in \rquote 
84 followed by a new technological revolution. In fact, it was in 1989 that Tim Berners-Lee produced his paper on the Wor
ld Wide Web. But that, one could argue, was it. Ann and Berkeley taught him the value and skill of very high level close empirical research. There are two kinds of empirical research combined in his books of that period \endash 
 number crunching and tracing the historical sequence (the economic history approach). Remains firmly convinced that this is the way to understand deep spatio-economic processes. This was also Schumpeter\rquote 
s method. This always had been his method but Berkeley taught him how to do it more closely and more carefully. American academic style is more deliberate and more careful. 
\par The central idea for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Containment of Urban England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  came out of the same idea as }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London 2000}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 ; one couldn\rquote t stop growth. In those books, he wanted to understand the pro
cess by which planners believed they could stop or shape growth. According to Raymond Unwin the idea of urban England was \lquote towns against a background of open country\rquote 
. A great achievement but unfortunately done grudgingly. Traced this in a series of histor
ic chapters, looking at five major urban regions and what happened there. Then Harry traced how the planning system worked. Then Ray Thomas showed that the planning system had worked, particularly in the New Towns. Much later, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Polycentric Metropolis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 (2006) Nick Green looked at commuter data and showed that in 2001 }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid16212032\charrsid1004843 self-containment}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  was still true of places more than around 50 miles from London \endash  suggesting that if you like self-containment, push growth out as far as you can. 
\par He didn\rquote t carry out any of the interviews \endash  was rather over-stretched at the time. 
\par Regarding his work \endash  all his Reading material was archived in Reading around 1983 (thanks to the presence of an archivist). Has had to throw out a lot of physical material since then. However, did 
get a PC early on and has saved all his work (and even drafts) on his own system. Has also kept press cuttings and has an extensive library. 
\par Came to the Bartlett as a result of the end of the Cold War
\par The Cold War ended, the aerospace industry in L.A. too
k a big hit and lots of aerospace bases were closed down. The result was that a big prop of the Californian economy was knocked from under. Prison guards unions and more backward parts of California wanted jails for the sake of economic development. It go
t
 to the point where the choice in California was between the university system and the jails. They cut the university system. The university had a lot of money in pensions and gave out a lot of golden handshakes, one of which he took, having just been off
ered a chair at UCL.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities of Tomorrow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  is a real favourite of his, the one he enjoyed writing most. Published in \rquote 87, his agent, Michael Sissons encouraged him to write a \lquote big book about cities
\rquote . Wanted to make it a very serious book. Had recently become obsessed by the notion of innovation and where it happened and decided to make this the organising principle of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities in Civilization}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
. His theory was that different cities became uniquely creative at different points in history and seldom repeated the tric
k. Came up with three and a half types of urban innovation: artistic/intellectual/philosophical; technical/industrial/innovative; the marriage of art and technology; urban innovation (cities innovating for themselves to solve their own problems). He frame
d chronological chapters inside analytical chapters. Discussed many of these analytical issues with friends at Berkeley and Alan Scott at UCLA. The book was his biggest failure and a huge disappointment. Was his first \lquote trade\rquote 
 (rather than academic) book. Not well publicised, not widely reviewed and never reviewed in academic publications. Didn\rquote t even earn its advance. He is still very pleased with it. 
\par His favourite visionary in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities of Tomorrow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  is Ebenezer Howard, his patron saint. He\rquote s been associated with the TCPA since the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid5602013\charrsid1004843 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
70s. Ebenezer looks down disapprovingly at the TCPA meetings. He was a practical visionary, who turned his visions into reality. Another hero is Frederick J. Osborn, who made the New Towns happen. It\rquote s for others to say if he should 
join their ranks but does describe himself as a practical visionary or practical Utopian. Currently has two obsessions \endash  High Speed Two and Boris Johnson\rquote s airport in the Thames Estuary. 
\par High Speed One \endash  one of the biggest things in his life. At this time
 (1990) he was at Berkeley. Thatcher had been forced out and Heseltine tried to be Prime Minister but ended up Secretary of State. Considers Heseltine the greatest political figure of the twentieth century after Churchill. Heseltine was keen to push throu
g
h the Channel Tunnel and as a result he was invited to come back to England and act as a Special Advisor on South East planning with special reference to the East Thames Corridor and the Channel Tunnel. The history of the Channel Tunnel: the railway line,
 
the push through cabinet. In 1992 left Berkeley and worked full time in the Department on both schemes: setting the line in detail, deciding the stations etc. Worked with three secretaries of state (Howard and Gummer after Heseltine) and each time had to 
be fired and re-appointed as a special advisor. In 1994 it was decided that it needed to turn into a civil service position. As a result the job was advertised. He applied and didn\rquote 
t get it (which he puts down to the psychological interview in which he said he\rquote 
d prefer to read a book than go to a party). The government decided that the line had to be built by private enterprise. He then joined Arup as advisor on their London and Continental bid and they won. 
\par Became convinced that high-speed rail was the key
 to the future of travel in Europe. Result of his experience of the 1990 TGV, passing trucks on the motorway that appeared to be stationary because the train was going so quickly. Thought that this would knock the planes from the air and take a lot of tra
ffic off the motorway. Did a lot of research into high speed trains. Even looked into high-speed rail in California which they\rquote 
ve just started building, 20 years later. Got very excited when High Speed Two became a possibility and is still involved and excited. 
\par The Bartlett is very complicated. Like Berkeley, it is a huge architecture school with a very small planning school. In neither place does planning properly relate to architecture. Thinks it \lquote can do, ought to and never, ever will.\rquote 
 The founder of the modern Bartlett, Richard Llewellyn Davies - himself an architect who became a planner \endash 
 had wanted to integrate them, but failed. Something about the ethos of the two professions makes it difficult. Became head of planning and had big tussles with the Dea
n who wanted to dissolve the School of Planning into a graduate school. He was adamant that a school with such a history should not be dismembered. Won that fight. Very difficult years. Stood down because he didn\rquote 
t want to do all the administrative work. Had hoped to build up, in the Bartlett, an \lquote organised research unit\rquote  (ORU) like he\rquote 
d had at Berkeley but failed. Research in the US is professionally organised, with a professional management team, a PA, a financial officer. You give them a research idea and they prepare the research proposal. We don\rquote 
t have this, generally, in British universities or in the Bartlett and thinks it\rquote s a great mistake. (Ironically the Berkeley lost theirs in the cuts). 
\par No one at the Bartlett has particularly influenced him. In 
general, has had to plough a rather lonely furrow there, doing his own thing (including a lot of interesting research). One of the most interesting pieces of research he did was through the Institute of Community Studies. 
\par The Institute was set up by Michael Young in 1954. He took it over, overseeing the last years of Michael\rquote s time at the Institute (which were difficult). Michael had been doing a study looking at Bethnal Green thirty years after }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Family and Kinship in East London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . He hoped to find happy white working class and discovered that they were all racist and were moving out to Essex. He couldn\rquote t bear the results so }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The New East End }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
only came out after his death, part of it written by Peter Hall. 
\par He made the Institute his own O.R.U. and hoped to make it the research arm of the Bartlett. Neither party was happy with that arrangement. Through the institute he did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid4333736\charrsid1004843 an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 E.U. research project, working with people in seven European cities to look at the phenomenon of the \lquote polycentric metropolis\rquote  (cities growing out into huge mega city regions). Resulted in a good book (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 The Polycentric Metropolis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
) - beautifully produced and very nice piece of research. The Institute wanted more of an action programme than he had provided and so he stood down and Geoff Mulgan took over, making it more of a social entrepreneurship organisation.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8407562 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
(Leaving Reading in peculiar circumstances. In 1987, still shuttling between Berkeley and Reading, applied for a chair of the ESRC. Took it and walked into a \lquote complete nightmare\rquote . It was s
upposed to move to Swindon, he fought the move, failed and resigned. Had already announced his departure from Reading who had already advertised his post. As a result went full time to Berkeley).
\par The story of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Working Capital}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . In 1997/8 a team of himself, I
an Gordon (LSE), Michael Harloe (Essex), Nick Buck (Essex) and Mark Kleinman (LSE) got a big ERSC grant. A joyous, intellectually stimulating experience. Met every month for three years and spent a day talking about research. Had a very good research team
 doing interviews. A lot of the work was number crunching. Then there was the interview part \endash 
 130 interviews in total carried out by trained researchers. Ended up with vast volume of transcript which had scarcely been used in the book. Offered to take over the transcripts. It took another five years to produce }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 London Voices, London Lives}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 .}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  Got all the interview material transcribed and edited it, knocking it \lquote into some kind of shape\rquote 
. You can never have too many interviews \endash  though it depends on what you\rquote re doing. Can\rquote t interview the dead though you should interview the \lquote nearly dead\rquote 
, especially people in public policy. For contemporary research, the interviews were fantastic. Learned a lot \endash  in particular that London is basically a rather happy city. Most bu
t some places are profoundly unhappy. The unhappy bits are the white working class areas in South-East London in particular (e.g. Bermondsey, Eltham). The white working class feel residual, shut out and resentful. They feel \lquote cheated\rquote 
 out of their }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8407562\charrsid1004843 birth right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  (which they\rquote 
d won in the Attlee welfare state) by the new immigrant arrivals who they saw as cheating the system. Southwark was doing a lot of social manipulation, movin
g black people from Peckham into the white working class bastions of Bermondsey. A lot of lifestyle clashes. Thinks planners should spend more time talking to local people \endash 
 provided it is dispassionate observation. Concluded that one must beware of social engineering by people who don\rquote t know what they\rquote re doing. 
\par The key contribution he has made to his field is \lquote understanding how cities work and trying to use that understanding to changing cities and city regions in a more intelligent way\rquote .
\par Relationship: Met Magda in an airport in Stockholm at 8 am on May Day 1965. Was then at Birkbeck, doing a reconnaissance trip for a field trip that summer. April 30}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\super\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
 in Sweden is the night that Swedish universities party. Colleagues were already there and went to a party
 where they met Magda. She needed a lift to Stockholm and they took her to the airport. She was hungover. He was hungover (from his own party the night before). Magda was originally a linguist then went back to college and took a Bachelors and Masters in 
Psychology. Was a consultant in the 1970s working for communications studies and planning. Supposed to do some work at Berkeley but it didn\rquote 
t happen, which made her very resentful and bored there. Did a lot of work for him, e.g. most of the ground work reading and note taking for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities and Civilisation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 . 
\par Hobbies: Regards his work as his hobby - has always hugely enjoyed it. If he\rquote s not actually working he\rquote s doing something related to what he\rquote s interested in \endash  thinking, reading, writing. Likes walking in the countryside. 
\par Friends: from Cambridge days: John Vaizey, Paul McQuail and his wife Susan, John Allen and Dorothy Williams, John Slee. From Berkeley: Mike and Mary Teitz, Guy and Karen Benvenice, Manuel Castells and his ex-wife Francoise. (Did a big study \endash 
 Technopoles of the World \endash  with Manuel). [In London: Paul Barker and his wife Sally, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid8407562 Brian }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 and Anne Lapping (these from New Society), Nick Falk and Esther Caplin, Pamela and Robert Beeson.
\par Currently heavily involved in an EU project \endash  Sustainable Integra
ted Tram-based Transport Options for Peripheral European Regions. Idea of running trams off city streets onto railway tracks in the countryside. Wants to do this in Blackpool among other places. (He was chair of the Urban Regeneration Company there for 4 
years. Didn\rquote t do much but fail to get a super casino built).
\par Looking back on his working career he is most proud of: High Speed One and the Thames Gateway. Also proud of some of his books, particularly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities of Tomorrow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843  and }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 Cities in Civilization}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
. Pleased to have been someone who influenced public thinking through his journalism. Very proud of his 50 years of journalism. Also proud of trying to build up university structures to do research more effectively (though this hasn\rquote 
t been very effective). 
\par Summing up his life as a whole, the worst single incident was the fight over the ESRC chairmanship. Had a bad impact on himself and his wife. Some fights he\rquote 
s had over the years in academic management have been bad. Had big fights with Ray Thomas over who was in charge of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
The Containment of Urban England }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid8658962\charrsid1004843 
project and with Kathy Pain over the Polycentric Metropolis project (she made a complaint about his management). Doesn\rquote t like clashing with people and found these very distressing. The high points were working with Heseltine \endash 
 an incredible experience \endash  and publication of the books. 
